
[1]petalism

   PET'ALISM, n. [Gr. See Petal.] A form of sentence among the ancient
   Syracusans,by which they proscribed a citizen whose wealth or
   popularity alarmed their jealousy, or who was suspected of aspiring to
   sovereign power; temporary proscription, or banishment for five years.
   The mode was to give their votes by writing his name on a leaf.
   Petalism in Syracuse answered to ostracism in Athens.
